265. The intransitive use of praecipitare with a reflective meaning occurs in Cicero and Caesar, and becomes especial- ly frequent in Livy and later writers—quasi is in more than one place found after compara- tives: see n. on Aul. 229. It is merely a compression of an original quam si, the middle stage qnamsei being supplied by the lex agraria, 1. 27. <Bu- cheler, lat. decl. p. 30.) Miiller observes (Plaut. Pros. p. 107)

that quasi stands for quam si only after comparatives in a negative sentence3 the nega- tion being in the present in- stance implied in peius. The construction saxo salire may be defended by v. 639, officio mi- grare. A Roman would natu- rally think of the Tarpeian rock from which criminals were fre- quently precipitated.
